1.e4
{ Active Bishops are nice, but at times they are merely claiming domination of unimportant real estate. In that case, you have to find (or create) something for them to do. The dream Bishop is both useful and active - it covers a lot of ground, but it is also serving a very specific (useful) purpose. [%mdl 32768] }
1...c5 2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 cxd4 4.Nxd4 Nc6 5.Nc3 Qc7 6.Be3 Nf6 7.Qd2 Bb4 8.f3 Nxd4
9.Qxd4 Bxc3+ 10.bxc3 b6
{ White's dark-squared Bishop is active in that it eyes two diagonals
(g1-a7 and c1-h6). However, the g1-a7 diagonal is blocked (the b6-pawn is a
rock) and the c1-h6 diagonal has nothing to do with the battle for the central dark squares (the d6-square in particular is screaming for the
Bishop's attention). In other words, it's active but not performing a useful function that relates to the other imbalances in the position. 

Of course, White's potential dark-square control is offset by the weak pawns
on the c-file, so Black has his chances too. Nevertheless, even if the chances are more or less balanced, it's still up to White to pose problems for his opponent by milking his positive imbalances for all they're worth. 

After 26 minutes thought, Grandmaster Volokitin played the most principled
move. } 11.Bc1 $1
{ Heading for a3 and, ultimately, d6. Now Black has to be very careful that
his King doesn't get stuck in the center. } 11...e5 $1
{ This fine move stops e4-e5 ideas and also chases the Queen off its
powerful central post. } ( { Worse were: } 11...Qc5 $2 12.Qxc5 bxc5 13.Ba3 d6
14.O-O-O Ke7 15.e5 dxe5 16.Bxc5+ Ke8 17.Bb5+ Bd7 18.Rxd7 Nxd7 19.Rd1 Rd8
20.c4
{ analysis by Volokitin, who says 'with the idea of Ba4, Ba3, c5 and c6 and
wins.' } ) ( 11...Bb7 $2 12.Ba3 Rc8 13.c4 Ba6
{ Or 13...e5 when both 14.Qd6 and 14.Qd2 are strong. } 14.e5 Ng8 15.Bd3 $1
Bxc4 16.O-O Bxd3 17.cxd3
{ and Black's lack of development and central King will leave him with
serious long-term difficulties. A sample line: } 17...Ne7 18.Rac1 Nc6
{ 18...Qb8 19.Rxc8+ Qxc8 20.Rc1 Qb7 21.Qb4 Nf5 22.Qe4 Qb8 23.Qc4 and
black's problems remain. } 19.Qe4 Qd8 20.d4
{ and Black is left with an unenviable defensive task. } ) 12.Qd2 O-O 13.Ba3
Re8 14.Bb5 a6 ( { Instead of } 14...Re6 $1
{ , in the actual game Black went down in defeat after ...a6. } ) ( 14...Re6
15.c4 Bb7 16.O-O-O { would have led to a more or less equal position. } )
15.Bd6 Qa7 16.Bc4 b5 17.Bb3 Bb7 18.O-O-O a5 19.a3 Rac8 20.g4 Rc6 21.g5 Nh5
22.Bxe5 Qc5 23.Qxd7 Qxe5 24.Bxf7+ Kf8 25.Bxe8 Rc7 26.Qd8 Qf4+ 27.Kb1 Rc8
28.Qb6
{ RULE While an active Bishop might look good, a useful Bishop trades style
for substance and addresses the deeper needs (both dynamic and defensive)
of a position. } 1-0

