{ This position has the same basic dynamics as found in the previous position. If White can win the e6-pawn, win the c6-square, or turn his e5 -pawn into a passer, the game will be his. If Black can stop White from doing those things, the game will be drawn. In this case the two areas of combat (e6 and c6) are just a step away from each other, so White wins (note that the game would be drawn if Black's Bishop stood on a2, b3, c4, or d5). [%mdl 32768] }
