1...g6
{ Though Bishops of opposite colors do increase the defender's chances of holding an inferior endgame in many cases, the same opposite-colored Bishops favors the attacker (in a middle game or endgame) if more pieces appear on the board. White is two pawns up. However, his queenside majority is frozen by Black's a-pawn and Bishop. What really makes Black's life a living hell is the combination of white's Rook and Bishop hitting f7. This completely immobilizes Black's army and leaves him waiting helplessly while White improves his position. The heat against f7, combined with the extra kingside pawn, ensures an easy victory for White. [%mdl 32768] }
2.g4 Bc3 3.f5 gxf5+ 4.gxf5 Bb4 5.f6 Bc3 6.Kf5
{ White calmly brings all his pieces to their optimum positions before
starting the final assault. When your opponent is helpless, enjoy the
luxury of putting every part of your position in perfect order. } 6...Bb4
{ Black's Bishop is forced to keep a permanent eye on b4. } ( 6...Bb2
{ allows } 7.b4 $1 axb4 8.a5
{ when the black b-pawn isn't going anywhere (thanks to the opposite
Bishops) while White's passed a-pawn will confidently head for a
transformative experience on a8. } ) 7.e6 fxe6+ 8.Bxe6+ Kh8 9.Kg6
{ And Black will soon be mated. To show you how important the existence of
the Rooks was to White's cause, let's look at the same position, sans
Rooks. @@StartFEN@@6k1/5pp1/7p/p3P3/PbB1KP2/1P4P1/7P/8 b - - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ Now Black’s King is free and after 1...Kf8 2.f5 Ke7 , White won’t be able
to win the game against correct defense (though he would be a fool not to try for a long, long time!). }
