21...Qf6 22.c3 Bd6 23.Nd2 Qe5 $1
{ An important maneuver for Black. By forcing g2-g3 (24. Nf1 is possible,
but then the Knight would be relegated to passive defense), Black hopes to
use his Queen and a8-Bishop to take advantage of the subsequent light-square holes that this pawn advance created. 

The battle is very interesting: White is doing his best to block his
opponent's light-squared Bishop while Black is doing everything in his power to create new diagonals for it that will ultimately allow game-saving counterplay against the white King. }
