Again: Unless you're sure that an aggressive/committal idea will bear fruit,
don't embark on an adventure that will only add to your defensive chore by creating new weaknesses in your own camp! Since 26... f5 didn't get the job done, Black should tighten up her position first. Perhaps a chance for ...f7-f5 will appear later, perhaps not. But there's no shame in being realistic and
accepting that the opponent's two Bishops are better than your Bishop and Knight. Once you make this sober determination, you should seek the usual anti-Bishop pair ideas (try to exchange one of the Bishops), get all your pieces into play, and create a solid 'wall' that's devoid of weak points. }
