16...a5 17.c3 a4 18.Bc2 b4 { or } ) 16.exd5 Bd7 17.Rfe1
{ Now we can see the point of White's 15. Nd5 - the former e4-pawn has
moved off the e-file and onto d5 where it gains space and frees up that
file for its Rooks. This allows them to exert tremendous pressure against the e7-pawn. }
( { GM Maurice Ashley: The most accurate continuation was } 17.Bxg7 Kxg7
18.f5 { , consistent with the idea of opening files. } 18...Bxf5 19.g4
{ brings pain on f7, and after 18...gxf5 19.Rfe1 Re8 20.Qf4 , a rook lift
is coming. } ) 17...Re8 ( 
{ GM Maurice Ashley: Black missed a chance here. Again, } 17...a5 $1
{ would have offered Black counterplay. } 18.c3 a4 19.Bc2 Bf5 $1
{ This is the engine speaking! } 20.Bxf5 Qxf5 21.Rxe7 a3 { The point. } 22.b3
Re8 { Fighting for the open files. Both } 23.Rde1 Bxd4+ 24.cxd4 Rxe7 25.Rxe7
Rc8 { and } 26.Re8+ Rxe8 ) 18.c3 h5
{ A move based on fear. Black was worried about g2-g4 and makes a move to
prevent that advance and also to make f5 accessible to black's Bishop.
However, the cure is worse than the disease since now Black's kingside is seriously weakened (as shown by the rest of the game). }
19.Re3
{ White intends to double on the e-file and increase his pressure against
e7. Chess is easy to play when you have an open road to a glaring weakness
(e7). However, the trick isn't in using these things (anyone can do that), it's in creating them! }
19...Bf5 ( { Calmly following his plan. The alternative, } 19...Bxd4 20.Rxd4
Bf5
{ , allows White to make use of the same strong Bishop maneuver that's seen
in the game. } ) 20.Bxg7 Kxg7 21.Rde1
{ Moves don't get more obvious or natural than this! Doubling on the e-file
will force two black pieces to play babysitter to the e7-pawn. Note how
powerful White's doubled Rooks are in comparison to their passive black counterparts on a8 and e8. }
21...Qd7
{ Black thinks he has everything under control, but White's next move shows
that he's badly mistaken. } 22.Bd1 $1
{ Suddenly Black's Bishop is about to be surrounded by g2 -g4. } 22...Qc7 ( 
{ Stopping g2-g4 by } 22...h4 { runs into } 23.Qf2
{ when the h4-pawn becomes Black's latest 'targeted for assassination'
unit. } ) ( 22...a5 23.g4 hxg4 24.hxg4 Bb1 25.f5 $1
{ gives White a strong attack. For example: } 25...gxf5
{ 25...Bxa2 26.Rxe7! Rxe7 27.f6+ Kg8 28.Rxe7 } 26.Qf4 f6 27.g5 Be4 28.gxf6+
exf6 { 28...Kxf6 29.Rxe4 } 29.Rg3+
{ and Black can resign. 

The rest of the game was pretty straightforward. } ) 23.g4 hxg4 24.hxg4 Bc8
25.f5 f6 26.Kg2 Bb7 27.g5 Qc4 28.Bb3 Qh4 29.Re4 Qh8 30.Rxe7+ Kf8 31.Qe4 Rxe7
32.Qxe7+ Kg8 33.Qxb7 ( 33.Qe6+
{ mates. However, I was so happy to snap off his Bishop that I didn't
bother looking for anything else. } ) 33...Rf8 34.Rh1 Qg7 35.Qxg7+ Kxg7
36.gxf6+
{ RULE A half-open file is often used to exert tremendous pressure against
weak enemy pawns. In this case 'weak' alludes to pawns that can't be
protected by other pawns. } 1-0

