{ Our next example shows a pawn sacrifice that directly addresses the
imbalances and goals that both sides were trying to achieve. } 1.d4
{ [%mdl 32768] } d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.a4 Bf5 6.e3 e6 7.Bxc4 Bb4
8.O-O O-O 9.Qe2 Bg6 10.Ne5 Nbd7 11.Rd1 Nxe5 12.dxe5 Nd7 13.f4 Qc7 14.Na2 Be7
15.e4 Nc5 16.Nc3 Rfd8 17.Rf1 Qd7 18.g4 h6 19.f5 Bh7 20.Be3 Qc7 21.f6 Bf8
22.fxg7 Kxg7 23.g5
{ This position is an easy read: Black's King is vulnerable and needs to be
cared for while white's pawn structure is a mess. Quite simply, Black will
have the advantage if he can find a safe haven for his King! 

Note how I didn't mention the threat of gxh6+. The reason is that one should
have a firm grasp of the imbalances (and the goals that their existence creates) before thinking about threats and replies to them. Now that we know what both sides are trying to achieve (White wants to attack the enemy King, Black wants to find a safe home for it and then punish white's
weak central pawns), the correct move for Black will make perfect sense. }
23...Bg6 $1
{ Played instantly. All of a sudden, Black's weak points (f7 is cemented,
and h5 is no longer a landing space for White's Queen) are solidly
defended, and white's position begins to creak and whine. 

Why is 23... Bg6 a hard move to find? We've been conditioned to avoid losing
material. In this case, you are giving up a pawn with check, so the mind automatically screams, 'Don't let him take it!' and blinds you to all other possibilities. That's why creating an imbalance-oriented base of knowledge about every position you reach is so important -
knowing a position's priorities allows you to step beyond the emotive mind and make decisions where logic, not emotion, rules. }
( { Browne hoped for } 23...hxg5 24.Qh5
{ when White's pieces are getting uncomfortably close to Black's King. } )
24.gxh6+ ( 24.b4 { is answered by } 24...Qxe5 ) 24...Kh7
{ White's a pawn ahead but the bits on e5, e4, and h6 are like overripe
fruit that Black can pick whenever he wants to. Equally important is the
black King's new situation-it's found some welcome cover on h7 and the white pawn on h6 actually plays the role of traitor since it's suddenly
giving shelter to the opposing King. 

I felt very confident here, but both of us now had only 3 minutes to make 16
moves! } 25.Bf4 Be7 ( { The critical move (and my original intention) was }
25...Rd4 $1 26.Be3 Rad8 $1 27.Bxd4 Rxd4 28.Rad1 Rxd1 29.Rxd1 Qxe5
{ when Black has all the play. But h2-h4-h5 ghosts began to nag at me and,
having no time for a deep look, irrationality won out and I decided to stop
the h-pawn in its tracks. } ) ( { I passed on } 25...Nd7 { due to } 26.h4 )
26.Rf2 Rd4
{ Going after the e5-pawn by 26.. Nd7!? was also tempting, but the clock
was ticking and a decision had to be made! } 27.Rg2 Rg8 28.Be3 Qxe5 $6
{ I had been dying to sacrifice the Exchange all through this game, and now
I jumped at the chance. However, this was not the best moment to do so. } ( 
{ The safer } 28...Rd7 { would have left Black firmly in charge since }
29.Bf4 { is strongly met by } 29...Bf6 $1 ) 29.Bxd4 Qxd4+ 30.Kh1 ( 
{ I had thought that I stood better here, but a quick look convinced me
that things are actually far from clear: } 30.Kh1 Nxe4
{ 30...Kxh6 with an edge is best, but it didn't occur to me during the
game. } 31.Bd3 Nxc3 32.Bxg6+ Rxg6 33.bxc3 Qxc3 34.Rf1 Bf6 35.Rxg6 Kxg6
{ With no time left, neither side wanted to touch this position! 

I should point out that offering various material imbalances is a part of
many highly respected openings (we'll stress positional sacrifices here, and not attack-based sacs). A few examples will follow. }
