15@@EndFEN@@ 15...Qc7 16.Nd4! making immediate use of the pin along the c-file. 16...Bd7 17.Qb3 Qb6 17...Qc8 18.Rac1 a5 19.Bh3 and Black is lost.
18.Qxb6 axb6 19.Nf5 is very strong. 2) @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2b1pp/1qn1pp2/8/8/P3BNP1/1PQ1PPBP/R2R2K1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@ 15...Qa6 16.Ne1! Ne5 16...e5 17.Be4 f5 18.Bd3 b5 19.Qb3+ wins the b5-pawn. 17.Nd3 Nxd3 17...Qc4 18.Qc1! A very accurate move that makes sure the Rooks will protect each
other. Also fine is the obvious 18.Rac1 , though that gives Black 18...Qxc2 19.Rxc2 Rd8 pinning the Knight to the d1-Rook. 18...Qxc1 19.Raxc1 Nxd3 20.Rxd3 a5 21.Bc5 Bxc5 22.Rxc5 and White's Rooks will penetrate into Black's position. 18.Rxd3 e5 19.Rc1 Be6 20.Qc7 and White wins material. 3) @@StartFEN@@r1b2rk1/pp2b1pp/1qn1pp2/8/8/P3BNP1/1PQ1PPBP/R2R2K1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@ 15...Qa5 16.Nd4 Nxd4 17.Rxd4 e5 17...Rd8 18.b4 Qe5 19.Rxd8+ Bxd8 20.Rd1 and White's pieces are raking Black's queenside and both files. 18.Qc4+ Kh8 19.Rd5 embarrassing Black's Queen. 19...Be6 20.Rxa5 Bxc4 21.Bxb7
Rab8 22.Rxa7 Bxe2 23.a4 And the queenside pawns will win the game. 

Notice how these lines kept Black under severe pressure, tormented his
Queen, and also allowed White to make full use of the open c- and d-files.) }
) 15...e5 16.Be3 Qc7 17.Rac1 Be6 18.h3 $2
{ Another lazy move, and now White's advantage is more or less gone (18.
