{ All the holes that were so graphically displayed in the previous example
no longer exist! The b5- and d5 -squares can both be made inaccessible to
White's pieces by ...c7-c6, e4 is now defended by the f5-pawn, and the f5- and h5-squares are firmly defended by the g6-pawn. }
1...e4 { [%mdl 32768] } 2.f4 c6 3.Nc3 Rd7
{ Followed by ...Red8, Black is for choice due to his strong Bishop, the
fact that White's Knight no longer has any advanced squares to enjoy, and
his mobile center which can kick into action at some point via ...d6-d5. 

More often than not, experienced opponents won't knowingly create a hole in
their own position without good reason. Nevertheless, holes are often handed to you on a silver platter, but you can only get mileage out of such mistakes if you notice how to create them and make use of the opportunity presented. }
