is } 8.bxc5 Rc2 9.Qa4 Ne2+ 10.Kh2 Rd2
{ and the dual threat of 11... Nxf4 and 11... Nc3 wins material and the
game. } ) 8...Ne6 9.R4f3 Qb2 10.R3f2 Rxf2 11.Rxf2 Qxb4 12.Qa2 Qd4 13.Bf1 Qe5
14.Kg2 Nd4
{ And Black is a pawn up and can also claim a far superior minor piece. 

PHILOSOPHY Fully embrace your 'inner square'. 

Are you getting a feel for this? Do you think you can begin creating weak
squares in the enemy camp? If so, you're ready to go a step further-let's take the initial position and make a 'slight' adjustment. }
