7.Kf1 Kf4
{ There's little doubt as to which King is the powerhouse and which is the
goat. Sometimes a single square, and the desire to reach that square, is
all it takes to turn things in your favor. } 8.Ke2 Re7 $1 9.Kf1 $4 ( 9.Bxa6
$4 d5 { traps the Bishop. } ) ( 9.Rg1 d5 10.Bb3
{ is a better defense, the idea being that } 10...f5 $4 { allows } 11.Rg6
{ when White is suddenly doing well. However, instead of blundering, simply
10...Rb5 keeps up the pressure and assures an enduring plus. } ) 9...Kxf3
10.Bxa6 d5 11.exd5 Rxe1+ 12.Kxe1 Re8+ 13.Kf1 Re2 14.Ra1 Rxf2+ 15.Kg1 Rg2+
16.Kh1 Be3
{ White resigned since ...Kg3 followed by ...Rh2 mate is impossible to
meet. } 0-1

