1...bxa5 $3
{ Level: 1800-2200. White has an obvious advantage in central and kingside space (a static plus that can turn dynamic at the drop of a hat) , and also has some pressure (statics and dynamics) on Black's position (he can open the a-file at will and kingside pawn breaks must always be anticipated) . Not relishing the prospect of a passive defense, Yusupov finds a surprising way to activate his army. Explaining the Rating Spread The ...bxa5 capture, which severely weakens Black's pawn structure, goes against most players' training. However, I feel that some class 'A' players (1800-1999) might be attracted to the b8-Rook's newfound activity and, as a result, would find the courage to cast their structural fears aside. [%mdl 32768] This ruptures Black's queenside pawn formation (thus giving White a static advantage in space and structure) but turns the formerly dead Rook on b8 into a serious dynamic contender on the open b-file. }
2.Rxa5 Rb3 3.Rc2 $6 { Okay, but a bit passive. } ( 3.e5
{ The best move is most likely } 3...fxe5 4.fxe5 Be7 5.Rxd8+ Bxd8 6.Rxa7 Ke8
$1
{ A calm tightening move that defends d8 and takes the sting out of Ra8.
The obvious 6...Bh4+ actually forces White's King to a better position
after 7.Kf3 when 7...Bd5+ is happily met by 8.Kf4 7...Rxc3 allows 8.Ke4 when White is a tiny bit better in both cases. Note that 6...Rxc3?? loses to
7.Ra8 } 7.Bd4
{ 7.Ra8? Bd5 has to be met with the slightly embarrassing 8.Ra1 8.Ra2??
Bh4+ 9.Kg1 Rb1+ picks up the Rook on a2. 8.Rc8?? loses to 8...Kd7 8...Bh4+
9.Kf1 Rxc3 gives Black an initiative (his pieces are far more active than White's), though White should be able to hold a draw. 7.Bd2?? Rb2 and
White's already lost: 8.Ke1 Bh4+ 9.Kd1 Bb3+ 10.Kc1 Rc2+ 11.Kd1 Rxc3 Mate! 11.Kb1 Rxd2 is of course White's best, but he might as well resign in that case. 7.Bd3 Rxc3 8.Bf5 Kf7 }
7...Rb2 8.Kf1 Rb1+ 9.Kg2 Rb2 10.Kf3 $4
{ Playing for the loss. Correct was 10.Kf1 Rb1+ with a draw by repetition.
} 10...Bd5+ 11.Ke3 Bg5+ 12.Kd3 { 12.Kf2 Bc4 wins a piece and the game. }
12...Rd2#
{ It's amazing how many tricks and mates there are in the position, a
testament to the power of active pieces! } ) 3...Ra3 4.Rh5 ( 
{ Another trap is } 4.Rxa3 Bxa3 5.Bxa7 $4 Bb3
{ and the Rook is trapped! 5.c4 a5 6.Ra2 Bb4 } ) 4...Kg8 5.c4 Bb4 6.Rb5 a5
7.c5 ( { No better is } 7.Bc5 Rh3 8.Bxb4 axb4 9.Rxb4 Bxg4 10.Kg2 h5 ) 7...Ra2
$4 ( 7...Rb3 { was correct when White has to scramble for equality: } 8.c6 a4
9.f5 Bf7 10.Bf4 Rc8 11.Rb7 Ba5 12.Be3 a3 13.Bc4 ) 8.Rxa2
