1.e4
{ The Alekhine Defense (1. e4 Nf6) is another Hypermodern opening that was actually toyed with long before Hypermoderns existed! [%mdl 32768] }
( 
{ The oldest example I could find was from 1802 (!) in the game Madame de
Remusat - Napoleon I, Paris. } 1.e4 Nf6 2.d3 Nc6 3.f4 e5 4.fxe5 Nxe5 5.Nc3
Nfg4 6.d4 Qh4+ 7.g3 Qf6 8.Nh3 Nf3+ 9.Ke2 Nxd4+ 10.Kd3 Ne5+ 11.Kxd4 Bc5+
12.Kxc5 Qb6+ 13.Kd5 Qd6#
{ I don't know if Allgaier saw this game, but he analyzed 1. e4 Nf6 in 1819
and decided that it was garbage. This opening wasn't given any respect
until Alekhine used it twice in 1921 to score a win and a draw against Saemisch and Steiner - then it was off to the Hypermodern races with various
adventurous players goading White's center pawns forward in an attempt to smite them if they dared to go too far! }
) 1...Nf6 2.e5 Nd5 3.d4 d6 4.c4 Nb6 5.f4 dxe5 6.fxe5 Nc6 7.Be3 Bf5 8.Nc3 e6
9.Nf3 Be7 10.d5 ( { The older main line is } 10.Be2 O-O 11.O-O f6 12.exf6
Bxf6
{ when Black's piece pressure against the center creates a position with
more or less equal chances for both sides. Pegoraro's move avoids the
balanced game that 10. Be2 offers and instead tries to use the center pawns to push Black right off the board. }
) 10...exd5 11.cxd5 Nb4
{ Suddenly white's pawns have high-stepped into enemy territory and d5 is
about to be treated as a foodstuff. White's pawn center looks more imposing
than ever, but its imminent demise means that he has to attack with all his might - it's too late to revert back to quiet positional play, now pure
dynamics lead the dance! } 12.Nd4
{ Attacking f5 and also defending against ...Nc2+. } 12...Bd7 ( 
{ The more natural } 12...Bg6 { has been shown to lose by force. } ) 13.Qf3
{ Defending d5 and threatening a2-a3. Now it's Black's turn to show some
enterprise! } 13...c5 $1
{ Since ...Nc2 + would follow if the d4-Knight moved, White has no choice
by to capture Black's c-pawn, thereby destroying what remained of his
oncemighty pawn center. } 14.dxc6 bxc6 15.e6
{ Trying to keep Black's King in the center for as long as possible. } ( 
15.a3 c5 16.axb4 cxd4 17.Bxd4 O-O { is fine for Black: } 18.Bd3 Bc6 $1 )
15...fxe6 16.O-O-O { There's not a white center pawn in sight! } 16...N6d5
17.a3 Nxc3 18.Nxe6
{ Ah, there's nothing like the smell of napalm splashing over the board!
Unfortunately for White, he's the one getting cooked. } 18...Nca2+ 19.Kb1
Bxe6 20.Rxd8+ Rxd8 21.axb4 Nxb4 22.Be2 Rf8 23.Qh5+ g6 24.Qe5 Bf5+ 25.Ka1 Rd5
26.Qb8+ Kf7 ( { White didn't like what was about to happen to him. After }
26...Kf7 27.Qxa7 Nc2+ 28.Ka2 Nxe3
{ White will be behind in material if he doesn't recapture } 29.Qxe3
{ Not to mention lines like 29.Rc1 Rd2 30.Qxe3 Ra8+ 31.Kb3 Rb8+ 32.Kc3 Bb4+
33.Kc4 Be6+ } 29...Ra5+ 30.Kb3 Rb8+ { is no less painful: } 31.Kc3 Bf6+
32.Kd2 Rxb2+ 33.Ke1 Ra1+ 34.Kf2 Rxh1 { 34.Bd1 Bg4 } ) 0-1

