{ We'll consider two ways a passed pawn can take on a very dynamic stance.
One is similar to the Passed Pawn Tango, which we just looked at, and the
other is the use of the pawn as an attacking unit. } 1.d4 { [%mdl 32768] } d5
2.c4 e6 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.Bg5 Be7 5.e3 O-O 6.Nf3 Nbd7 7.Qc2 h6 8.Bh4 c5 9.Rd1 Qa5
10.Nd2 cxd4 11.exd4 e5 12.dxe5 Nxe5 13.Nb3 Qb4 14.Bxf6 Bxf6 15.cxd5 Nc4
16.Bxc4 Qxc4 17.Qe2 Bxc3+ 18.bxc3 Qxc3+ 19.Rd2 Bd7 20.O-O Rfe8 21.Qd1 Bb5
22.Re1 ( 22.Qa1 $1 { is just a little better for Black. } ) 22...Rxe1+
23.Qxe1 Re8 24.Qd1 Ba4 $4 ( { Both players missed the surprisingly strong }
24...Re4 $1 { when the threat of 25... Qe5 wins outright! Note that } 25.Nd4
Ba4 $1 { is gin. } ) 25.h3
{ White managed to survive some terrible opening play and can now can sit
back and celebrate his new lease on life-there are no more serious enemy
threats to fear and his passed d-pawn is a definite asset. Surprisingly for a player of Leonhardt's class, Black makes two poor moves in a row,
allowing White to take over the game. } 25...Bxb3 $6
{ Black should retain this Bishop since it keeps an eye on the d5-pawn's
path through d7. With all the minor pieces off, Black can only blockade
with a Queen or Rook, and neither of those powerful pieces really wants to be employed as a babysitter. In fact, this mistake allows me to present a
highly useful rule: The ideal plan for a player with an advanced passed pawn is to exchange all the minor pieces, leaving both sides with a Queen and Rook(s) vs. Queen and Rook(s). This creates possibilities of obtaining the kind of advantageous Queen endgames discussed earlier and also makes
the blockade of the passer uncomfortable. 

Note that the Queens should be retained since that piece's power makes the
defending King's participation in the defense rather risky. } ( 25...b6
{ was better, taking the c5-square away from the Knight. } ) ( 
{ Other moves that could have also been considered were } 25...Qb4 { and } )
( 25...Re4 26.Re2 Bxb3 27.axb3 Rd4
{ though the endgame should be drawn after } 28.Re8+ Kh7 29.Qb1+ Qd3
{ 29...g6 30.Re7 } 30.Qxd3+ Rxd3 31.Rb8
{ In all these cases, Black would have retained some slight pressure on
White's position. } ) 26.axb3 Rd8 $2
{ With his last two moves, Black has allowed White to realize the rule
calling for the creation of a Queen and Rook vs. Queen and Rook situation.
} ( { Much better was } 26...Qe5 $1 27.d6 Qe1+ 28.Qxe1 Rxe1+ 29.Kh2 Re8
{ when, with the Queens off, Black's King can safely enter the fray - if it
can reach d7, the black King would not only blockade the pawn, but would
also begin the process of attacking and winning it! Of course, White has various tries that will try to take advantage of Black's present passivity (a
well-timed Rd2-c2-c7 is one, while g4, Kg3, and f2 -f4-f5 grabs a serious amount of space). But accurate defense should easily give Black the half point. }
) 27.d6 Qc6 28.d7 Kf8 29.Qg4 Qe6 30.Qb4+ Qe7 31.Qc3
{ Black is now doomed to eternal passivity. The rest of the game saw White
enjoying a good 'Cat and Mouse,' patiently and relentlessly torturing his
opponent until he finally cracked. } 31...Qe6 32.Qc5+ Qe7 33.Qc7 b6 34.Kh2 a6
35.g3 b5 36.b4 f6 37.h4 Kf7 38.h5 Kf8 39.Kg2 Qe4+ 40.Kh2 Qe7 41.Kg1 Qe1+
42.Kg2 Qe4+ 43.Kh2 Qe7 44.Rd4 Kf7 45.Rd2 Kf8 46.Kg2 Qe4+ 47.Kh2 Qe7 48.Rd6
Kf7 49.Qc6 Qe5 50.Kg2 Ke7 51.Rd3 Kf7 52.Rd2 Ke7 53.Rd3 Kf7 54.Kg1 Qe1+ 55.Kg2
Qe5 56.Rd2 Ke7 57.Rd3 Kf7 58.Kg1 Qe1+ 59.Kg2 Qe5 60.Kg1 Qe1+ 61.Kg2 Qe5
62.Rd2 Ke7 63.f4 Qe6 64.Qc5+ Kf7 65.f5 Qe4+ 66.Kf2 Qe5 67.Qxe5 fxe5 68.Kf3
Ke7 69.Ke4 Rxd7 70.Rxd7+ Kxd7 71.Kxe5 Ke7 72.g4 Kf7 73.Kf4 Kf6 74.g5+ hxg5+
75.Kg4 Kf7 76.Kxg5 a5 77.bxa5 b4 78.a6 b3 79.a7 b2 80.a8=Q b1=Q 81.Qa7+ Kf8
82.Kg6 1-0

